node.text: Own a piece of Einstein history! The bricks from Einstein’s childhood home in Ulm, Germany were recently unearthed and are now being made into commemorative plaques for true Einstein fans! The proceeds will go to help build a new discovery center and museum in Einstein’s hometown. Watch this video to learn more and visit www.alberteinstein.rocks to reserve your piece of history.

node.title: Own a piece of Einstein history!

node.text:
Even after astronomical observations convinced Einstein that the universe is expanding there remained the question of what drove the universe to expand in the first place – that is, what sparked the Big Bang. Join physicist Brian Greene to explore one prominent possibility: repulsive gravity ignited a brief but powerful burst off cosmic inflation.

@brian_greene111 @worldscifest #yourdailyequation

node.text:
One of the greatest surprises in the past few decades is the discovery that the expansion of space is speeding up. Join physicist Brian Greene for a discussion of our best explanation: gravity can be repulsive and can thus drive the distant galaxies to rush away ever more quickly.

@brian_greene111 @worldscifest #yourdailyequation

node.title: Repulsive Gravity, Dark Energy, and Accelerated Expansion

node.text:
Shortly after Einstein published his new theory of gravity, his general theory of relativity, researchers realized that it predicted that the universe should expanding – a prediction subsequently confirmed by astronomical observations. And if it is expanding today, then running the cosmic film back toward the beginning suggests a highly dense and energetic starting point – the big bang. Join physicist Brian Greene for a visual explanation of the essential ideas as well as an introduction to the underlying math that yields these conclusions.

@brian_greene111 @worldscifest #yourdailyequation

node.title: Einstein, The Big Bang, and the Expansion of the Universe

Albert Einstein's General Theory of Relativity, phrased in terms of warps and curves in space and time, provides our most refined description of the gravitational force. Join physicist Brian Greene for a visual exploration of Einstein's most profound discovery and the equations he triumphantly announced in 1915.

@brian_greene111 @worldscifest #yourdailyequation

@brian_greene111 @worldscifest #yourdailyequation

node.text:
WATCH: Physicist Brian Greene talks time travel. Not the kind of time travel you encounter in sci-fi, but real time travel – the kind that's written into the laws of physics and understood using the time dilation equation. Watch to learn more about how and why our perceptions of space and time are not fixed, but relative.

@brian_greene111 @worldscifest #yourdailyequation #timetravel #backtothefuture

node.title: Time Dilation: Einstein's shocking insight on the nature of time

node.text:
Posted @withregram • @nobelprize_org 26-year-old Albert Einstein formulated the two postulates of special relativity on 30 June 1905.

The postulates of special relativity:
1. The principle of relativity
The laws of physics are the same in all inertial frames of reference.

2. The constancy of speed of light in vacuum
The speed of light in vacuum has the same value c in all inertial frames of reference.

The speed of light in vacuum c (299792458 m/s) is so enormous that we do not notice a delay between the transmission and reception of electromagnetic waves under normal circumstances.

The speed of light in vacuum is actually the only speed that is absolute and the same for all observers as was stated in the second postulate.

Photo: Einstein in 1904 or 1905, Wikimedia Commons.
